Note:
This file provides low-level memory operations as compiler intrinsics.

These functions replace the C runtime memory functions:
- memory_get_byte/int32/int64/integer/pointer - read from memory
- memory_set_byte/int32/int64/integer/pointer - write to memory
- memory_copy - replaces memcpy (forward bytewise copy)
- memory_copy_backward - backward bytewise copy (memmove forward-overlap path)
- memory_fill - replaces memset (renamed from memory_set)
- memory_compare - replaces memcmp

All operations are platform-independent compiler intrinsics.
The compiler lowers these to appropriate platform-specific instructions:
- x86_64: mov, rep movsb/stosb/cmpsb
- ARM64: ldr, str, ldp, stp, memory copy loops
- RISC-V: lb, sb, lw, sw, ld, sd, memory loops
- PowerPC: lbz, stb, lwz, stw, ld, std, memory loops
- MIPS: lb, sb, lw, sw, ld, sd, memory loops

This is a foundation primitive with NO dependencies.
:End Note

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LOW-LEVEL LOAD/STORE INTRINSICS
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Raw memory access primitives implemented in inline assembly. The high-level
Note: memory_get_*/memory_set_* helpers below compose calls to these. They are
Note: deliberately kept in this file rather than a separate platform/ file
Note: because they have no logical alternative on any architecture - every CPU
Note: backend lowers them to a single load/store instruction, so the asm form
Note: is documentation. (When ports for non-x86-64 architectures are wired,
Note: each platform contributes its own version of this file via the build
Note: system; until then, the x86-64 form covers Linux x86-64 builds.)
Note: Stack-frame convention: stage1 stores parameter N at -8N(%rbp); the
Note: function's Let-declared result variable follows at the next slot.

Process called "load_byte_unsigned" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # addr at [rbp-8], result at [rbp-16]
        mov rcx, [rbp-8]
        movzx rax, byte ptr [rcx]
        mov [rbp-16], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "load_int32_signed" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # addr at [rbp-8], result at [rbp-16]
        mov rcx, [rbp-8]
        movsxd rax, dword ptr [rcx]
        mov [rbp-16], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "load_int64" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # addr at [rbp-8], result at [rbp-16]
        mov rcx, [rbp-8]
        mov rax, [rcx]
        mov [rbp-16], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "store_byte" takes addr as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Inline Assembly:
        # addr at [rbp-8], value at [rbp-16]
        mov rcx, [rbp-8]
        mov rax, [rbp-16]
        mov byte ptr [rcx], al
    End Assembly
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "store_int32" takes addr as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Inline Assembly:
        # addr at [rbp-8], value at [rbp-16]
        mov rcx, [rbp-8]
        mov rax, [rbp-16]
        mov dword ptr [rcx], eax
    End Assembly
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "store_int64" takes addr as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Inline Assembly:
        # addr at [rbp-8], value at [rbp-16]
        mov rcx, [rbp-8]
        mov rax, [rbp-16]
        mov [rcx], rax
    End Assembly
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Memory Read Operations
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "memory_get_byte" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read a single byte from memory at ptr + offset
    Note: Returns the byte value (0-255)
    Note: Compiler intrinsic - platform independent
    Note: Lowers to: movzbq (x86_64), ldrb (ARM64), lbu (RISC-V), lbz (PowerPC), lbu (MIPS)

    Let address be ptr plus offset
    Let result be proc load_byte_unsigned with address
    Return result
End Process

Process called "memory_get_int8" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read a signed 8-bit integer from memory at ptr + offset, sign-extended
    Note: to 64-bit. Composes from memory_get_byte and applies sign-extension
    Note: if the byte value is >= 128 (top bit set).
    Let unsigned_byte be proc memory_get_byte with ptr, offset
    Let bit7_mask be 128
    If unsigned_byte is greater than or equal to bit7_mask:
        Return unsigned_byte minus 256
    End If
    Return unsigned_byte
End Process

Process called "memory_set_int8" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Write the low 8 bits of value to memory at ptr + offset.
    Note: Negative values are stored two's-complement; the store_byte path
    Note: truncates everything above the bottom 8 bits, so positive and
    Note: negative inputs both produce the correct byte pattern.
    Let address be ptr plus offset
    Let dummy be proc store_byte with address, value
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "memory_get_qword" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Quad-word alias for memory_get_int64. "qword" is x86 terminology;
    Note: some callers (especially low-level memory marshallers) reach for this
    Note: name.
    Return proc memory_get_int64 with ptr, offset
End Process

Process called "memory_get_int16" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read a signed 16-bit integer from memory at ptr + offset, sign-extended
    Note: to 64-bit. Used by half-precision float (Float16) and 80-bit float
    Note: (Float80) bit-pattern access in softfloat.runa, and by serializers
    Note: that read network/file headers carrying 16-bit fields.
    Note: Composed from two byte reads (little-endian) so it works without a
    Note: platform-specific load_int16 intrinsic. The sign-extension step
    Note: replicates bit 15 across the upper 48 bits when the value is negative.
    Let address be ptr plus offset
    Let lo be proc load_byte_unsigned with address
    Let hi_addr be address plus 1
    Let hi be proc load_byte_unsigned with hi_addr
    Let hi_shifted be hi multiplied by 256
    Let value be lo plus hi_shifted
    Note: sign-extend: if bit 15 (0x8000) is set, value is negative.
    Let sign_bit be hi multiplied by 256
    Let bit15_mask be 32768  Note: 0x8000
    If value is greater than or equal to bit15_mask:
        Return value minus 65536  Note: subtract 2^16 to sign-extend
    End If
    Return value
End Process

Process called "memory_get_int32" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read a 32-bit integer from memory at ptr + offset
    Note: Returns the int32 value (sign-extended to 64-bit)
    Note: Compiler intrinsic - platform independent
    Note: Lowers to: movslq (x86_64), ldrsw (ARM64), lw (RISC-V), lwa (PowerPC), lw (MIPS)

    Let address be ptr plus offset
    Let result be proc load_int32_signed with address
    Return result
End Process

Process called "memory_get_int64" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read a 64-bit integer from memory at ptr + offset
    Note: Returns the int64 value
    Note: Compiler intrinsic - platform independent
    Note: Lowers to: movq (x86_64), ldr (ARM64), ld (RISC-V), ld (PowerPC), ld (MIPS)

    Let address be ptr plus offset
    Let result be proc load_int64 with address
    Return result
End Process

Process called "memory_get_integer" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Alias for memory_get_int64 (Integer is 64-bit in Runa)
    Return proc memory_get_int64 with ptr, offset
End Process

Process called "memory_get_pointer" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read a pointer (64-bit address) from memory at ptr + offset
    Note: Alias for memory_get_int64
    Return proc memory_get_int64 with ptr, offset
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Memory Write Operations
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "memory_set_byte" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Write a single byte to memory at ptr + offset
    Note: Only the lowest 8 bits of value are written
    Note: Returns 0
    Note: Compiler intrinsic - platform independent
    Note: Lowers to: movb (x86_64), strb (ARM64), sb (RISC-V), stb (PowerPC), sb (MIPS)

    Let address be ptr plus offset
    Let dummy be proc store_byte with address, value
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "memory_set_int16" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Write a 16-bit integer to memory at ptr + offset (little-endian).
    Note: Only the low 16 bits of value are written, in two's-complement form
    Note: when value is negative. Returns 0.
    Note: Composed from two byte writes since there is no platform-specific
    Note: 16-bit store intrinsic in this layer. We mask value to 16 bits via
    Note: bitwise_and so the two byte stores carry the same low-16 pattern
    Note: as a native movw would. Plain integer division by 256 truncates
    Note: toward zero, which is WRONG for negative values (e.g. -1/256 = 0
    Note: not -1 / 0xFF); the bitwise_and approach handles both signs.
    Let address be ptr plus offset
    Let mask16 be 65535  Note: 0x0000FFFF
    Let narrowed be value bitwise_and mask16
    Let lo_byte be narrowed bitwise_and 255
    Let dummy_lo be proc store_byte with address, lo_byte
    Let hi_addr be address plus 1
    Let hi_byte be narrowed shifted right by 8
    Let dummy_hi be proc store_byte with hi_addr, hi_byte
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "memory_set_int32" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Write a 32-bit integer to memory at ptr + offset
    Note: Only the lowest 32 bits of value are written
    Note: Returns 0
    Note: Compiler intrinsic - platform independent
    Note: Lowers to: movl (x86_64), str (ARM64 w-reg), sw (RISC-V), stw (PowerPC), sw (MIPS)

    Let address be ptr plus offset
    Let dummy be proc store_int32 with address, value
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "memory_set_int64" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Write a 64-bit integer to memory at ptr + offset
    Note: Returns 0
    Note: Compiler intrinsic - platform independent
    Note: Lowers to: movq (x86_64), str (ARM64 x-reg), sd (RISC-V), std (PowerPC), sd (MIPS)

    Let address be ptr plus offset
    Let dummy be proc store_int64 with address, value
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "memory_set_integer" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Alias for memory_set_int64 (Integer is 64-bit in Runa)
    Return proc memory_set_int64 with ptr, offset, value
End Process

Process called "memory_set_pointer" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Write a pointer (64-bit address) to memory at ptr + offset
    Note: Alias for memory_set_int64
    Return proc memory_set_int64 with ptr, offset, value
End Process

Process called "memory_set_qword" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Quad-word alias for memory_set_int64. Symmetric to memory_get_qword.
    Note: "qword" is x86 terminology; many low-level memory marshallers in the
    Note: compiler frontend (diagnostics, import_system, intentional_recovery)
    Note: reach for this name. The handwritten runtime build_runtime/primitives/
    Note: memory_core.s also exposes a memory_set_qword symbol that tail-calls
    Note: memory_set_int64 with identical semantics.
    Return proc memory_set_int64 with ptr, offset, value
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Bulk Memory Operations
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "memory_copy" takes dest as Integer, src as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Copy length bytes from src to dest
    Note: Platform independent - compiler generates optimal code
    Note: Lowers to: rep movsb (x86_64), ldp/stp loop (ARM64), word-aligned loop (RISC-V/PowerPC/MIPS)
    Note: Returns 0

    Note: Byte-by-byte copy loop (compiler will optimize to bulk operations)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let byte_value be proc memory_get_byte with src, i
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_byte with dest, i, byte_value
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "memory_copy_backward" takes dest as Integer, src as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Copy length bytes from src to dest, iterating from the highest index
    Note: down to index 0. This is the reverse-direction counterpart to
    Note: memory_copy and is the correct primitive for forward-overlap moves,
    Note: i.e. when dest > src AND dest < src + length. In that case a forward
    Note: copy would read source bytes that have already been overwritten by
    Note: the moving destination window; a backward copy reads each source
    Note: byte BEFORE the destination write reaches its slot, preserving the
    Note: source value all the way through the move.

    Note: When dest <= src OR src + length <= dest there is no overlap and
    Note: memory_copy is preferred (forward sequential access pattern is
    Note: friendlier to hardware prefetchers). The two primitives together
    Note: compose into the memmove semantics implemented in memory_safety.

    Note: Platform independent - compiler generates optimal code
    Note: Lowers to: std + rep movsb after direction-flag set (x86_64),
    Note: descending ldp/stp loop (ARM64), descending word loop (RISC-V/
    Note: PowerPC/MIPS). The DF must be cleared on x86_64 before returning
    Note: so the System V ABI invariant "DF=0 on call/return" holds.
    Note: Returns 0

    Note: Byte-by-byte backward copy loop. i starts at length-1 and decrements
    Note: to 0 inclusive. We use a do-while-style guard (length <= 0 -> noop)
    Note: by checking the condition up front; the loop body itself terminates
    Note: when i reaches -1.
    If length is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be length minus 1
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let byte_value be proc memory_get_byte with src, i
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_byte with dest, i, byte_value
        Set i to i minus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "memory_fill" takes dest as Integer, value as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set length bytes at dest to value (only low 8 bits of value)
    Note: Platform independent - compiler generates optimal code
    Note: Lowers to: rep stosb (x86_64), stp loop (ARM64), word-aligned loop (RISC-V/PowerPC/MIPS)
    Note: Returns 0
    Note: Renamed from memory_set to avoid confusion with memory_set_* functions

    Note: Byte-by-byte fill loop (compiler will optimize to bulk operations)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_byte with dest, i, value
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "memory_compare" takes ptr1 as Integer, ptr2 as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lexicographic byte comparison matching POSIX memcmp() semantics.
    Note: Returns -1 when ptr1[i] < ptr2[i] at the first differing byte,
    Note:          0 when length bytes are identical,
    Note:          1 when ptr1[i] > ptr2[i].
    Note: Bug #423 fix - the pre-fix implementation returned 0 for equal and
    Note: 1 for ANY difference (sign-less), which broke every ordered caller
    Note: (bytes_compare, sorted maps, B-tree node comparisons, etc.).
    Note: Platform independent. Lowers to: rep cmpsb (x86_64), ldp comparison
    Note: loop (ARM64), word-aligned comparison (RISC-V/PowerPC/MIPS).

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let byte1 be proc memory_get_byte with ptr1, i
        Let byte2 be proc memory_get_byte with ptr2, i

        If byte1 is less than byte2:
            Return 0 minus 1
        End If
        If byte1 is greater than byte2:
            Return 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Memory Allocation Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "memory_zero" takes ptr as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Zero out length bytes at ptr
    Note: Convenience wrapper for memory_fill(ptr, 0, length)
    Return proc memory_fill with ptr, 0, length
End Process
